qasm_simulator = Aer.get_backend("qasm_simulator")
statevector_simulator = Aer.get_backend("statevector_simulator")
In[4]:
def run_on_simulators(circuit):
    statevec_job = statevector_simulator.run(circuit)
    result = statevec_job.result()
    statevec = result.get_statevector()

    num_qubits = circuit.num_qubits #used this just to show such a function exists to get a number of qubits
    # circuit.measure([0,1],[0,1]) # Measure q0,q1 and associate them with c0,c1
    circuit.measure([i for i in range(num_qubits)],[i for i in range(num_qubits)]) 

    qasm_job = qasm_simulator.run(circuit, shots=1024).result()
    counts = qasm_job.get_counts()

    return statevec, counts
In[5]:
circuit = QuantumCircuit(2,2)
statevec, counts = run_on_simulators(circuit)

# Plot bloch sphere representation of qubits after applying Hadamard gate to the first qubit, then applying CNOT gate
# Since the qubits will be entangled, the result on bloch sphere would not be so sensible. 
# In this case, for example, it makes sense to look at the Q sphere.
circuit = QuantumCircuit(2,2)
circuit.h(0)
circuit.cx(0,1) # 0-> control qubit, 1-> target qubit
statevec, counts = run_on_simulators(circuit)
plot_bloch_multivector(statevec)
Out[9]:
In[10]:
plot_histogram(counts)
Out[10]:
In[11]:
# Plot bloch sphere representation of qubits after rotating around x axis
circuit = QuantumCircuit(2,2)
circuit.rx(math.pi/4, 0) #Rotate Pi/4 around x axis, apply on the first qubit
circuit.rx(math.pi/2, 1) #Rotate Pi/2 around x axis, apply on the second qubit
statevec, counts = run_on_simulators(circuit)
plot_bloch_multivector(statevec)

# If I apply Hadamard gate to the first qubit, then apply CNOT, it would entagle the qubits.
# To reverse this operation, I would apply one more CNOT and then Hadamard gate. This would put it back to 00.
# What happens if we add a Z gate between two CNOTs? It would give 01, in other words, it would alter the rotation.
# Thus, phase may or may not affect the outcome
